SIMPLE: meridional
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Meridional
<hw>Me*rid"i*o*nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧ridional</ets>, L. <ets>meridionalis</ets>, fr.
<ets>meridies</ets> midday. See <er>Meridian</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the meridian.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having a southern aspect; southern;
southerly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Offices that require heat . . . should be
<qex>meridional</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meridional distance</b></col>, <cd>the distance or
departure from the meridian; the easting or westing.</cd> --
<col><b>Meridional parts</b></col>, <cd>parts of the meridian in
Mercator's projection, corresponding to each minute of latitude from the
equator up to 70 or 80 degrees; tabulated numbers representing these
parts used in projecting charts, and in solving cases in Mercator's
sailing.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meridionality</ent>⟦br⟧
